    <section id="tribute-info">
      <p>
        Augusta Ada King, Countess of Lovelace (1815â€“1852), was an English mathematician and writer, chiefly known for her work on Charles Babbage's early mechanical general-purpose computer, the Analytical Engine. Her notes on the engine include what is recognized as the first algorithm intended to be carried out by a machine, and as a result, she is often regarded as the first computer programmer. Ada's foresight into the capabilities of computing devices extended well beyond number crunching to general-purpose processing of symbols and data.
      </p>
